### Java ###
*.class
*.log
hs_err_pid*
replay_pid*

### Maven (backend + frontend, if both use Maven) ###
target/
pom.xml.tag
pom.xml.releaseBackup
pom.xml.versionsBackup
pom.xml.next
release.properties
dependency-reduced-pom.xml
buildNumber.properties
.mvn/timing.properties
.mvn/wrapper/maven-wrapper.jar

### Gradle (only relevant if you end up using Gradle instead of Maven) ###
.gradle/
build/
!gradle/wrapper/gradle-wrapper.jar
!gradle/wrapper/gradle-wrapper.properties

### Spring Boot ###
# Local-only config overrides that may contain secrets (DB creds, JWT secret, etc.)
# Keep the real application.properties/yml committed — just ignore *local* override files.
application-local.properties
application-local.yml
application-local.yaml
.env

### SQLite database files ###
# The whole point of persistent storage is that it survives a restart —
# but that means it's *runtime data*, not source code, so it shouldn't be
# committed. Each teammate (and the grader) should get a fresh/empty DB
# when they run the project, generated by Hibernate's ddl-auto on first run.
*.db
*.db-journal
*.db-shm
*.db-wal
*.sqlite
*.sqlite3

### JavaFX / frontend build output ###
# Same target/ as backend if frontend is also a Maven module — already covered above.
# If you package a runnable jar via jlink/jpackage, ignore that output too:
/frontend/target/
*.jar
!.mvn/wrapper/maven-wrapper.jar

